Chapter 1
Cohren
0430 Itania-Time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He especially hated it because he was responsible for waking up all the others in his company. Silently, he got up from his bunk, put on his combat suit, threw his protective vest over it, and retrieved his belongings from the locker, being careful around a particular small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Everything he needed hung there, such as his breathing apparatus or his special glasses. After checking his ammunition pouches, he left the barracks quietly. Outside, the mud and ice crunched under his boots.
He pulled a lighter out of one jacket pocket and a cigarette out of the other. He lit it and took a brief puff before opening the door a little. In the past week, he had come up with various ways to rouse the men and women under his command. He no longer used the set alarm clock, as it usually didn't work and only produced a faint hiss from the speakers.
“Wake them up?” Cohren turned around and saw Zugführer Nemic approaching him.
„Yes“, answered Cohren.
„What do you want to try this time?“
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and a few others came towards him already in full gear.
„Good morning,“ said Craith.
„What have you woken up for?“, asked Cohren.
„Also, first of all, we weren't in the mood to wait for what you might come up with today. And secondly, the assault troops who rise first should be allowed to choose their morning ration,“ one of the men replied, Ravik. „And you know how bad the food can be.“
„Good point, Sergeant,“ said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a switch. In the barracks, a loud, shrill alarm sounded. Inside, he heard muffled curses and people moving around in confusion.
„Come on, Valturi,“ said Nemic. „One would think they'd have learned by now to wake up at the same time as you.“
„Well, my trainees from the training camp have,“ Cohren replied and pointed to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. „However, the platoon and company leaders also know that they must rise before their units.“
A moment later, the rest of the company emerged. They had everything they needed, from personal items to the necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, while others appeared irritated.
„Good morning,“ said Cohren cheerfully.
„With all respect, Sir, why do you have to wake us up like this?“ asked a Storm Trooper sergeant.
„Because the regular alarms are shit and because Daybreak won't oversleep,“ said Cohren.
„Pack all your personal belongings,“ Cohren continued. As senior lieutenant and executive officer of the company, he was responsible for overseeing and supporting them together with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. „We won't be coming back here. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for the final checks and to pack the daily rations.“
The members of the Exodus Company dispersed quickly. They were part of the second Storm Trooper Division, Second Army. Before they were combined, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company had been split, and that was the main reason why Cohren had mixed feelings regarding his promotion to senior lieutenant.
Cohren und Nemic, der Führer des ersten Zuges, gingen nebeneinander im Schein der vielen generatorbetriebenen Lampen der vorgeschobenen Einsatzbasis. Die meisten hatten rot getöntes Glas, um von feindlichen Bombern nicht entdeckt zu werden. Daybreak hatte auf Wild-Weasel-Angriffe aus der Luft und am Boden zurückgegriffen, um sie zu bekämpfen.
„Ein neuer Tag und eine neue Aufgabe für die Höllenhunde“, sagte Nemic mit einem trockenen Lachen. „Wohin schicken sie uns?“
„Eine vorgeschobene Einsatzbasis außerhalb von Ianlos. Wir werden den Bodenangriff unterstützen“, antwortete Cohren und zog an seiner Zigarette. Er gab Craith eine Teilschuld daran, dass er mit dem Rauchen angefangen hatte, aber ein Jahr im Einsatz veränderte einen, deshalb sagte er nichts.
„Scheiße. An der Front wird es immer schlimmer“, murmelte Nemic. „Alle Nachrichten lauten: «Unterstützt die Kriegsanstrengungen. Schickt Hilfe an die Kurgan-Front.» Wie wäre es mit Hilfe für die Howland-Front?“
„Amen, Bruder“, sagte Cohren und schnippte die Reste seiner Zigarette in den Schlamm. „Immerhin machen wir mit dem ersten bewaffneten Zug los und müssen nicht laufen. Hauptmann Shaw sollte schon da sein.“
“Has Shaw made a ride-sharing opportunity clear for us?”, Nemic asked a bit surprised.
“Yes. He is actually not as bad as I thought. Though not particularly sociable, one can get along with him.”
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone and put his backpack on. “All units of the Exodus Company will meet at the West Vehicle Park when they are ready. We will depart with the first armed convoy at 0500.”
In rapid succession, he received responses from the platoon leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they all arrived here. The four had become close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren felt like he knew them forever, even though it was only two years. They were platoon leaders, but Craith had taken command of the second convoy for a week now, as the previous leader had been medically discharged after being shot by a Daybreak sniper.
On their way to the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic noticed a group of about eight Kronos battle tanks and four armored personnel carriers. Their crews were walking around, ensuring their machines were ready for action. Quickly, Cohren spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking to the commander of the armed convoy. As they approached, Shaw looked over at them and came toward them, as always with a neutral expression on his face.
“Leutnant Nemic… Leutnant Valturi…“ He said Cohren was moving slower, while he looked at Cohren's pistol holster and then looked up again. „The company is ready, I assume?“
